    <node id="chunk:f409c7a7896517577ff3">
      <data key="d2">chunk:f409c7a7896517577ff3</data>
      <data key="d3">Chunk</data>
      <data key="d4">data/debugg_sample/alan_turing.jsonl</data>
      <data key="d5">Alan Turing was born in London, England in 1912. He studied at King's College, Cambridge and later earned his PhD from Princeton University.

During World War II, Turing worked at Bletchley Park, where he played a crucial role in breaking the German Enigma code. He developed the Bombe, an electromechanical device used to decipher Enigma-encrypted messages.</data>
      <data key="d6">56</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chunk:967f21d0515276f22a42">
      <data key="d2">chunk:967f21d0515276f22a42</data>
      <data key="d3">Chunk</data>
      <data key="d4">data/debugg_sample/alan_turing.jsonl</data>
      <data key="d5">ode. He developed the Bombe, an electromechanical device used to decipher Enigma-encrypted messages.

After the war, Turing worked at the National Physical Laboratory and later at the University of Manchester. He is widely considered the father of theoretical computer science and artificial intelligence. His 1950 paper "Computing Machinery and Intelligence" introduced the Turing Test.</data>
      <data key="d6">54</data>
      <data key="d7">1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chunk:e0ea2f7b6bdb7e55a31b">
      <data key="d2">chunk:e0ea2f7b6bdb7e55a31b</data>
      <data key="d3">Chunk</data>
      <data key="d4">data/debugg_sample/alan_turing.jsonl</data>
      <data key="d5">cial intelligence. His 1950 paper "Computing Machinery and Intelligence" introduced the Turing Test.

Turing also made significant contributions to mathematical biology, publishing work on morphogenesis. He died in 1954 in Wilmslow, England.</data>
      <data key="d6">32</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chunk:981720eb52cecf7f80a8">
      <data key="d2">chunk:981720eb52cecf7f80a8</data>
      <data key="d3">Chunk</data>
      <data key="d4">data/debugg_sample/marie_curie.jsonl</data>
      <data key="d5">Marie Curie was born in Warsaw, Poland in 1867. She is best known for her pioneering research on radioactivity. She discovered the elements polonium and radium.

Curie worked at the University of Paris, where she became the first female professor. In 1903, she received the Nobel Prize in Physics along with Pierre Curie and Henri Becquerel for their work on radioactivity.</data>
      <data key="d6">61</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chunk:3a298cc444d403faae22">
      <data key="d2">chunk:3a298cc444d403faae22</data>
      <data key="d3">Chunk</data>
      <data key="d4">data/debugg_sample/marie_curie.jsonl</data>
      <data key="d5">Nobel Prize in Physics along with Pierre Curie and Henri Becquerel for their work on radioactivity.

In 1911, she won a second Nobel Prize, this time in Chemistry, for her discovery of radium and polonium. She founded the Curie Institutes in Paris and Warsaw, which remain major medical research centers today.

Marie Curie died in 1934 in Passy, France from aplastic anemia, likely caused by her long-term exposure to radiation.</data>
      <data key="d6">70</data>
      <data key="d7">1</data>
    </node>
